Hi Oliver,

Please see below.

&gt; There&#39;s been talk about NS providing smoot=
h fitness landscapes, but is there evidence that the landscape is actually =
smoother? Another alternative might be that there are simply more path ways=
 for evolution to take. Or in your minds are these the same thing? It sound=
s like you think they are at least related, if not one and the same thing, =
Joel, when you say &quot;I do believe that gradients of novelty are often smooth=
er than objective fitness gradients, perhaps because there are more of them=
&quot;. Not sure how interesting this is, but maybe it&#39;s important to distinguis=
h between methods that produce smoothness versus many path ways.

The metap=
hor of the fitness landscape is not a perfect one, nor has it been made ver=
y concrete, but I believe that most biologists would think of the two as se=
parate. I believe what matters for the issue of self adaptive mutation rate=
s is the frequency with which mutations produce beneficial mutations. For e=
xample, even if a population has many paths to ultimately increase fitness,=
 if they all require going through a fitness valley, there would still be a=
 downward pressure on mutation rates. Similarly if a few paths exist that d=
o not require traversing a valley, but they are so rare as a percent of the=
 overall number of paths that evolution in practice never finds them, then =
the pressure to reduce mutation rates would be the same as if those paths d=
id not exist. The key to producing situations in which mutation rates are n=
ot floored is having many paths that do not require traversing fitness vall=
eys, and I think we can all agree that novelty search does that much better=
 than objective-driven search.


&gt; The paper on NS plateaus sounds interest=
ing, I look forward to seeing it! I (think) I have seen this occur in my ow=
n experiments. A lot of recent work has used multi-objective EAs to combine=
 novelty and objective search. In light of NS plateaus I now think this nee=
ds be implemented very carefully (more carefully than I have been doing at =
any rate ;)), since if the objective search has too much influence it could=
 prevent exploration beyond one or two mutations, preventing the EA from ge=
tting beyond the NS plateau. Perhaps others have already figured this out a=
nd I&#39;m late to the game: some work has probabilistically applied the object=
ive function (don&#39;t have any cites off the top of my head) to mitigate this=
).

You may be thinking of the probabilistic multi-objective algorithm that=
 Jean-Baptiste, Hod and I introduced in the following paper:

Clune J, Mour=
et J-B, Lipson H (2013) The evolutionary origins of modularity. Proceedings=
 of the Royal Society B. 280: 20122863. pdf: http://goo.gl/2vzFv
&gt; 
&gt; Final=
ly, on a side note, last night I came across this article about a long peri=
od of stagnance (between 1.7 billions and 750 million years ago) in natural=
 evolution: http://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22229672.900-why-did-evol=
ution-stall-during-the-boring-billion.html#.U2Vv4HWSz0I . The article talks=
 about how the (physical) environment during this period was very stagnant,=
 but then plate tectonics kicked off, perturbing evolution to produce new (=
more complex) species. Joel&#39;s comment about NS, &quot;there&#39;s no equilibrium in =
the system because in order to stick around in the population, you must alw=
ays be doing something different than you were in the past&quot;, made me think =
about it, and about how NS is perhaps the ultimate perturbation mechanism.
=
&gt; 
&gt; Cheers,
&gt; Oliver
&gt; 
&gt; 
