&gt; From: neat@yahoogroups.com [mailto:n=
eat@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of Jeff Clune
&gt; Sent: Saturday, May 03, 2014=
 7:38 AM
&gt; To: neat users group group
&gt; Subject: Re: [neat] Self-adaptive M=
utation Rates, Novelty Search and CMA-ES
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; Hello Joel and =
Vassilis,
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; I=92ll respond in this thread since it is focused on =
the issue of self-adatptive mutation rates and novelty search. I=92ll first=
 respond to Vassilis then Joel=92s original comments. Please see below. 
&gt; =

&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; Self-adaptive mutation rates are a terrible idea:
&gt; 
&gt; Jeff, than=
ks for pointing this out. That is an interesting paper! To be honest I have=
n&#39;t read it before; so, you are saying that self-adaptive mutation rates ca=
n be more effective on smoother fitness landscapes, correct?
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; No=
velty Search:
&gt; 
&gt; Joel, could novelty search be seen as a way of creating =
a smoother fitness landscape? If yes, then based on what you said, is this =
the reason why self-adaptive mutation rates work better when coupled with n=
ovelty search?
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; I agree with you. Self-adaptive mutation =
rates work fine on smooth landscapes. Of course, landscapes on any interest=
ing, non-trivial problem are rugged, so that means that generally self-adap=
tive mutation rates are a very bad idea. Novelty search, however, makes the=
 conversation more complex. I agree with you that NS smoothes out landscape=
s, making self-adaptive mutation rates far less pathological. That said, I=
=92m not yet sure that self-adaptive mutation rates are actually a good ide=
a with Novelty Search (see below). 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; I believe the idea=
 of self-adaptive mutation rates formed the basis for more advanced evoluti=
on strategies such as CMA-ES. I am not trying to defend CMA-ES here, which =
I agree with Jeff that it works differently than the basic approach of enco=
ding the mutation rates in the genotype. However, I am wondering whether a =
combination of novelty search with CMA-ES would be a good approach in speed=
ing up the search for novel behaviours.
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; Of course, I can see so=
me disadvantages of CMA-ES, an example being that the genotype is a vector =
of real numbers with a fixed size... What do you think?
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; =
I don=92t think what makes CMA-ES effective has anything to do with self-ad=
aptive mutation rates. I think that it=92s advantage is in learning correla=
tions. But, as far as I know, it=92s still forced to mutate genomes accordi=
ng to those correlations. I must admit I don=92t know the CMA_ES literature=
 at all, but my guess is that if you tried CMA-ES with and without a mutati=
on rate on the genome, you=92d get the same result I report in my paper: as=
 long as the landscape is rugged (i.e. the problem is non-trivial), evoluti=
on will floor mutation rates and the result will underperform the best, fix=
ed mutation rate. Anyone know the literature enough to know if I=92m right?=
 Or anyone care to give it a try?
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; Regarding Joel=92s claim that=
 whether self-adaptation is a good idea depends on whether fitness is based=
 on an objective or NS:
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; I love Joel and Ken=92s paper looking i=
nto whether self-adaptative mutation rates (SAMR) are a better idea with NS=
. As I said above, it makes sense that SAMR would be less bad with NS, beca=
use NS smooths out landscapes and eliminates peaks, but is it actually a *g=
ood* idea instead of just being less bad? On that question I am still agnos=
tic pending further research. 
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; One reason is because of &quot;novelt=
y plateaus=94, a concept my students and I introduce in our last, not-yet-a=
nnounced GECCO paper. Novelty plateaus exist when, during novelty search, m=
utating the current population does not immediately produce new behaviors. =
For example, once the low-hanging fruit is consumed, it might take 5 specif=
ic mutations to produce a new behavior (assume that all intermediate mutati=
ons have no effect on behavior). In that case, NS cannot reward those stepp=
ing stones to the new behavior, and thus there is no incentive to have a hi=
gh mutation rate. Since most mutations break things (producing the very un-=
novel behavior of doing little or nothing), I hypothesize that having a hig=
h mutation rate will be selected against when on such a novelty plateau. In=
 other words, think of the long, flat lines of fitness you (Joel) mentioned=
: We hypothesize that those long-flat lines also exist in terms of generati=
ng new behaviors and, if we&#39;re right, I think there would be a pressure to =
lower mutation rates during such periods, even though keeping the mutation =
rate high is exactly what you need to cross the plateau. Of course, a lot o=
f this is speculation, and I think a paper on this subject would be very in=
teresting and worthwhile for the community.
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; Now let me argue ag=
ainst myself, since I=92m thinking through these issues by writing about th=
em in this thread! While I can imagine that novelty plateaus exist, for the=
 specific purposes of this conversation on mutation rates, I can=92t figure=
 out if they would actually cause selection for lower mutation rates, becau=
se even if you are not generating not-yet-seen-before behaviors, you can be=
 generating non-new behaviors in different regions of density in the archiv=
e=85meaning that you may truly always be on the side of a hill and not on a=
 neutral plateau. What do y=92all think?
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; An additional reason I=
=92m not yet ready to commit to the claim that SAMR is a good idea with NS =
is because your paper didn=92t show that SAMR did optimize mutation rates f=
or long-term adaptation. You did not sweep over the range of fixed mutation=
 rates and show that SAMR found those optimal rates, or outperformed them. =
Instead, you showed that it performed better than the parameters you had fo=
r the initial experiment. 
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; An final reason I=92m agnostic (so f=
ar) on the issue of whether SAMR helps with NS is because the evidence in y=
our paper, while very interesting, was also not overly strong or consistent=
. I hope you won=92t be offended and think I=92m critical of you and Ken or=
 the work. You may be right that SAMR+NS works, and it would be fascinating=
 if you are, but I would just like to see larger effect sizes, lower p-valu=
es, and more consistency across domains before taking the claim =93SAMR wor=
ks with NS=94 to the bank. Please see below for some of my specific reasons=
 for this claim. 
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; 1. I don=92t see self-adaptive mutation rates=
 helping a lot in your results: in some cases SAMR improved evolvability si=
gnificantly, but not in all, and in the cases where the difference is signi=
ficant, the effect size is very small and the variance and associated p-val=
ue are high. The same is true for performance, where self-adaptation only h=
elped in one domain, not all, and the difference was a jump from ~5% to ~10=
% (a doubling, which is rather impressive, but with a p-value of only &lt; 0.0=
5). I hope I didn=92t get any of these details wrong. I apologize if I did.=

&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; Personally I=92d prefer more tests before I really commit to=
 this conclusion and start drawing inferences from it. To repeat, I hope yo=
u don=92t mind that I point out that I=92d prefer more experiments and on m=
ore problems before fully committing to the view that self-adaptation helps=
 with novelty search. As I said, I do think the result is probably right, a=
s self-adaptation works well on smooth fitness landscapes, and NS does elim=
inate peaks and smooth landscapes. Moreover, I think it was an extremely cl=
ever and interesting question to ask and issue to raise: I=92m a big fan of=
 the paper, but I=92d still love to see follow-up studies on it because the=
 result is fascinating, but so far the evidence is not as strong as it coul=
d be. 
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; 2. You show that Eibd* (=93evolvability as defined as pr=
oducing immediate behavioral diversity=94) is better for NS with self-adapt=
ation, but
&gt; 
&gt;             a. The real proof is if these organisms actuall=
y evolve better in a new environment. It would be great to see those data. =
You have provided some evidence for improved long-term evolvability since p=
erformance was higher, but again that was only in one of the domains, and t=
he difference was not huge. 
&gt; 
&gt;             b. Did you look at what happe=
ned to the mutation rates? They may have still gone down, which could produ=
ce more Eibd, but at the cost of Elt* (Evolvability over the Long Term). 
&gt;=

&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; 3. You report that &quot;Initial experiments revealed that evolving a=
 single mutation power and rate for each entire genome is too coarse.=94 Th=
at suggests that the effect may not be that robust, and may be hard to take=
 advantage of in practice. I also noted that in the treatment that ultimate=
ly worked, you took an intermediate route of different mutation rates for d=
ifferent connections, but not one set of mutation rates per-connection. Out=
 of curiosity, did you also try that and find it didn=92t work? 
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
=
&gt; Overall, I do think that how bad self-adaptive mutation rates are depends=
 on the ruggedness of landscapes, and NS makes them less bad because it smo=
oths landscapes. However, I consider the question of whether SAMR are benef=
icial with NS to be a fascinating, open question that you have provided som=
e evidence for, but that we=92d all benefit from seeing a lot more research=
 into. 
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; Best,
&gt; 
&gt; Jeff
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt; 
&gt; *I=92m making these up as I=
 go along!
