Vassilis,&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;=
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;I=92ll respond in this thread since i=
t is focused on the issue of self-adatptive mutation rates and novelty sear=
ch. I=92ll first respond to&nbsp;Vassilis then Joel=92s original comments. =
Please see below.&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span =
style=3D&quot;font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Times, serif;&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u=
&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Self-adaptiv=
e mutation rates are a terrible idea:&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p c=
lass=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Jeff, thanks for pointing this out. That is an interesti=
ng paper! To be honest I haven&#39;t read it before; so, you are saying that se=
lf-adaptive mutation rates can be more effective on smoother fitness landsc=
apes, correct?&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&n=
bsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Novelty Search:&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;=
/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Joel, could novelty search be seen=
 as a way of creating a smoother fitness landscape? If yes, then based on w=
hat you said, is this the reason why self-adaptive mutation rates work bett=
er when coupled with novelty search?&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=
=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p cla=
ss=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;=
I agree with you. Self-adaptive mutation rates work fine on smooth landscap=
es. Of course, landscapes on any interesting, non-trivial problem are rugge=
d, so that means that generally self-adaptive mutation rates are a very bad=
 idea. Novelty search, however, makes the conversation more complex. I agre=
e with you that NS smoothes out landscapes, making self-adaptive mutation r=
ates far less pathological. That said, I=92m not yet sure that self-adaptiv=
e mutation rates are actually a good idea with Novelty Search (see below).&=
nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;=
/p&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div=
&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;I believe the idea of self-adaptive mutation rates =
formed the basis for more advanced evolution strategies such as CMA-ES. I a=
m not trying to defend CMA-ES here, which I agree with Jeff that it works d=
ifferently than the basic approach of encoding the mutation rates in the ge=
notype. However, I am wondering whether a combination of novelty search wit=
h CMA-ES would be a good approach in speeding up the search for novel behav=
iours.&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;=
/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Of course, I can see some disadvan=
tages of CMA-ES, an example being that the genotype is a vector of real num=
bers with a fixed size... What do you think?&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;=
div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p clas=
s=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;I=
 don=92t think what makes CMA-ES effective has anything to do with self-ada=
ptive mutation rates. I think that it=92s advantage is in learning correlat=
ions. But, as far as I know, it=92s still forced to mutate genomes accordin=
g to those correlations. I must admit I don=92t know the CMA_ES literature =
at all, but my guess is that if you tried CMA-ES with and without a mutatio=
n rate on the genome, you=92d get the same result I report in my paper: as =
long as the landscape is rugged (i.e. the problem is non-trivial), evolutio=
n will floor mutation rates and the result will underperform the best, fixe=
d mutation rate. Anyone know the literature enough to know if I=92m right? =
Or anyone care to give it a try?&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;Ms=
oNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Regardin=
g Joel=92s claim that whether self-adaptation is a good idea depends on whe=
ther fitness is based on an objective or NS:&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p=
 class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNorm=
al&quot;&gt;I love Joel and Ken=92s paper looking into whether self-adaptative muta=
tion rates (SAMR) are a better idea with NS. As I said above, it makes sens=
e that SAMR would be less bad with NS, because NS smooths out landscapes an=
d eliminates peaks, but is it actually a *good* idea instead of just being =
less bad? On that question I am still agnostic pending further research.&nb=
sp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;=
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;One reason is because of &quot;novelty pla=
teaus=94, a concept my students and I introduce in our last, not-yet-announ=
ced GECCO paper. Novelty plateaus exist when, during novelty search, mutati=
ng the current population does not immediately produce new behaviors. For e=
xample, once the low-hanging fruit is consumed, it might take 5 specific mu=
tations to produce a new behavior (assume that all intermediate mutations h=
ave no effect on behavior). In that case, NS cannot reward those stepping s=
tones to the new behavior, and thus there is no incentive to have a high mu=
tation rate. Since most mutations break things (producing the very un-novel=
 behavior of doing little or nothing), I hypothesize that having a high mut=
ation rate will be selected against when on such a novelty plateau. In othe=
r words, think of the long, flat lines of fitness you (Joel) mentioned: We =
hypothesize that those long-flat lines also exist in terms of generating ne=
w behaviors and, if we&#39;re right, I think there would be a pressure to lower=
 mutation rates during such periods, even though keeping the mutation rate =
high is exactly what you need to cross the plateau. Of course, a lot of thi=
s is speculation, and I think a paper on this subject would be very interes=
ting and worthwhile for the community.&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=
=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;No=
w let me argue against myself, since I=92m thinking through these issues by=
 writing about them in this thread! While I can imagine that novelty platea=
us exist, for the specific purposes of this conversation on mutation rates,=
 I can=92t figure out if they would actually cause selection for lower muta=
tion rates, because even if you are not generating not-yet-seen-before beha=
viors, you can be generating non-new behaviors in different regions of dens=
ity in the archive=85meaning that you may truly always be on the side of a =
hill and not on a neutral plateau. What do y=92all think?&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;=
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p cla=
ss=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;An additional reason I=92m not yet ready to commit to the =
claim that SAMR is a good idea with NS is because your paper didn=92t show =
that SAMR did optimize mutation rates for long-term adaptation. You did not=
 sweep over the range of fixed mutation rates and show that SAMR found thos=
e optimal rates, or outperformed them. Instead, you showed that it performe=
d better than the parameters you had for the initial experiment.&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/=
u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/di=
v&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;An final reason I=92m agnostic (so far) on th=
e issue of whether SAMR helps with NS is because the evidence in your paper=
, while very interesting, was also not overly strong or consistent. I hope =
you won=92t be offended and think I=92m critical of you and Ken or the work=
. You may be right that SAMR+NS works, and it would be fascinating if you a=
re, but I would just like to see larger effect sizes, lower p-values, and m=
ore consistency across domains before taking the claim =93SAMR works with N=
S=94 to the bank. Please see below for some of my specific reasons for this=
 claim.&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nb=
sp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;1. I don=92t see self-adapt=
ive mutation rates helping a lot in your results: in some cases SAMR improv=
ed evolvability significantly, but not in all, and in the cases where the d=
ifference is significant, the effect size is very small and the variance an=
d associated p-value are high. The same is true for performance, where self=
-adaptation only helped in one domain, not all, and the difference was a ju=
mp from ~5% to ~10% (a doubling, which is rather impressive, but with a p-v=
alue of only &lt; 0.05). I hope I didn=92t get any of these details wrong. =
I apologize if I did. &nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;=
u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Personally I=92d p=
refer more tests before I really commit to this conclusion and start drawin=
g inferences from it. To repeat, I hope you don=92t mind that I point out t=
hat I=92d prefer more experiments and on more problems before fully committ=
ing to the view that self-adaptation helps with novelty search. As I said, =
I do think the result is probably right, as self-adaptation works well on s=
mooth fitness landscapes, and NS does eliminate peaks and smooth landscapes=
. Moreover, I think it was an extremely clever and interesting question to =
